are very different than intrusive thoughts impulsive thoughts are often experienced by people with adhd and arise spontaneously impulsivity in people with adhd refers to a core symptom where individuals have difficulty controlling their immediate reactions or responses it can manifest in behaviors like interrupting others and having difficulties waiting for their turn individuals with adhd may experience fleeting thoughts that divert their attention from the task at hand but they typically do not attach intense significance anxiety or distress to those thoughts in contrast ocd intrusive thoughts can cause significant anxiety and distress examples of impulsive thoughts in someone with adhd can include 1 sudden creative bursts of innovative ideas unrelated to their task at hand 2 inability to filter thoughts that may flood the mind causing difficulty in prioritizing and sustaining attention this may lead to difficulties in decision making impulsive thoughts in people with adhd and intrusive obsessions in people with ocd differ in key aspects 1 nature of the thoughts impulsive thoughts in adhd arise spontaneously and are unrelated to the current task or context in contrast intrusive obsessions in ocd are repetitive and unwanted and cause distress and anxiety 2 control and intentionality impulsive thoughts in people with adhd are typically unintentional and occur without conscious effort whereas individuals with ocd experience intrusive obsessions as distressing and inconsistent with their own desires resulting in efforts to suppress or neutralize them 3 impact on behavior impulsive thoughts in people with adhd may lead to impulsive actions or difficulties in maintaining attention and focus intrusive obsessions in people with ocd on the other hand drive individuals to engage in compulsive behaviors or mental rituals aimed at reducing anxiety and neutralizing the distress caused by the obsessions recognizing the difference between impulsive thoughts in people with adhd and intrusive obsessions in people with ocd is essential for effective intervention strategies and it is possible to meet the criteria for both disorders here is a well being historically men have been socialized to suppress their emotions and maintain a stoic facade which can make it difficult for them to seek help or openly discuss their mental health struggles this societal expectation of masculinity can lead to feelings of isolation and shame when faced with emotional difficulties consequently many men may downplay or ignore their mental health issues which can exacerbate their condition over time several factors contribute to men s mental health challenges these include traditional gender roles societal expectations often dictate that men should be strong self reliant and unemotional this can create a barrier for men to express vulnerability seek emotional support or ask for help when needed these pressures can result in internalized stress anxiety and depression stigma mental health stigma remains a significant hurdle for men seeking therapy or openly discussing emotions is sometimes perceived as a sign of weakness or incompetence this stigma can prevent men from seeking professional help exacerbating their mental health issues and hindering their recovery suicide rates men face higher rates of suicide compared to women the reluctance to seek help and the tendency to internalize emotional distress can contribute to this alarming statistic society s expectation that men should handle their problems independently can make it challenging to identify warning signs or intervene in time substance abuse men may turn to substance abuse including alcohol and drugs as a coping mechanism for their mental health struggles this can further complicate their mental well being and lead to a cycle of addiction and deteriorating mental health addressing men s mental health requires a multi faceted approach that focuses on breaking down gender stereotypes and promoting open dialogue about emotions and well being encouraging men to seek help and providing accessible mental health resources tailored to their needs is crucial by fostering an environment that encourages emotional expression offering mental health education and dismantling the stigma associated with seeking support society can positively impact men s mental health outcomes it is essential for men to recognize that seeking help is a sign of strength not weakness through professional therapy support networks self care practices and a willingness to address their mental health concerns men can take proactive steps towards improved well being and a healthier mindset ultimately promoting men s mental health is about fostering an video_description: gem on thecastoffspod shares her personal journey from mental illness to mental wealth for years gem struggled with anxiety depression and other mental health challenges believing that her thoughts and emotions were a reflection of reality but after discovering the three principles a transformative approach to psychology and mindfulness gem experienced a profound shift in her understanding of the mind she learned that her thoughts were not absolute truths but rather passing mental events that she could observe and let go of through this new perspective gem was able to let go of her limiting beliefs and find a new sense of inner peace and resilience in this clip she shares her insights and advice for anyone struggling with mental health challenges offering hope and inspiration for those seeking a new path to mental wealth watch the full conversation here find out more donate sponsor listen subscribe to the podcast spotify apple google connect with oneminding website youtube instagram twitter facebook oneminding shares the three principles and their mission is to create a free revolution in the world of mental health and awakening this initiative was created by samantha hurst molls and gemma ramsden gemsays in 2021 they share a weekly podcast that points back to the innate wellbeing and peace of mind that lies within all of us join the revolution of the mind we are living in a world that is suffering from stress and mental health issues and it is getting worse every day many people feel hopeless and cannot see beyond what their mind is telling them and any unhealthy thoughts feelings that they may have there is limited help available to those without funding and many people are lost and do not know where to turn there is an understanding that takes us beyond our minds constant narrative and shows us that it is not in the analysis of the mind but the detachment and observation of it that frees us from mental distress and illness when understood this uncovers wellbeing and dissolves what looks like insurmountable issues and problems this understanding is called the three principles knowing this molls and gem wanted to find a way to video_title: what is social anxiety #shorts #lifehackshorts
video_description: one of the most prevalent types of anxiety that many people experience is social anxiety disorder in other words you re not the only one who struggles with social anxiety even around friends and other loved ones this crippling illness can make it challenging to interact socially especially if the socially anxious person feels scrutinised or criticised in any manner an individual with social anxiety may find it challenging to engage in simple social interactions such as conversing with the grocery store cashier or going on dates or attending job interviews some people have social anxiety when performing routine acts like eating or drinking in front of others because they worry about being rejected or humiliated as a result of how others see them the terror that comes with social anxiety disorder can often feel uncontrollable because it is so strong it may make it impossible for some people to attend job or school others might be able to persevere but even so they ll feel a lot of stress and anxiety and be completely worn out when they come home people with this kind of anxiety frequently start worrying about future social settings weeks in advance and others may wind up avoiding particular locations or events entirely
audio_transcript: social anxiety disorder is a common form of anxiety it hinders social situations including public speaking dating and job interviews simple tasks like talking to others or eating in public become challenging social anxiety disorder can cause physical symptoms such as rapid heartbeat sweating trembling and stomach discomfort the fear associated with social anxiety is intense and difficult to control it often leads to exhaustion after social interactions some individuals with social anxiety avoid specific events or places it is commonly mistaken for extreme shyness women especially teenagers are more susceptible to social anxiety disorder without treatment social anxiety can persist for years or even a lifetime for more information about social anxiety disorder please visit our website

video_title: bedtime procrastination and anxiety go hand in hand #therapy #shorts #anxiety
video_description: it s time to go to sleep you re lying in bed and you have 2 minutes left on netflix your brain starts to wander thinking about all the other things you could be doing like making plans for the next day yet you don t switch off the tv knowing that one more episode may be too much before you know it its 4am and you re feeling overwhelmed sound familiar you may be experiencing bedtime procrastination or revenge bedtime procrastination which is a common phenomenon that affects many people bedtime procrastination is when we find ourselves doing things that are a distraction from going to sleep such as watching television or checking social media in an effort to avoid thinking or doing more emotionally laden activities we may have put off during the day however the reason that his behavior is problematic is due to its potential physical and mental health impact according to research done in 2018 this behavior results in a collective six hours less of sleep per week thats hugely significant when we think of our sleep bank that s 312 hours yearly we know that sleep has such a major impact on our wellness and just an interested addition when researching this topic the term revenge was added to it in china this is because china is known for a 72 hour work week if not lots lots more and it was researched that this behavior in china manifested as a way for overworked individuals to take back control of their life what do you think is this something you ve experienced before

video_title: bipolar 2 from inner critic to inner friend #motivation #podcast #shorts #facts #selenagomez
video_description: some tips on how to go from inner critic to inner friend if you have bipolar empathize with your inner critic your inner critic is a part of you and it s trying to protect you from harm it may be telling you things like you re not good enough or you ll never succeed but remember your inner critic is wrong you are good enough and you can succeed challenge your inner critic s thoughts when your inner critic starts talking take a step back and ask yourself if the things it s saying are really true are you really a failure are you really not good enough chances are the answer is no your inner critic is just trying to scare you be kind to yourself the way you talk to yourself matters if you re constantly berating yourself it s going to be hard to feel good about yourself so start talking to yourself with more kindness and compassion focus on your strengths everyone has strengths and weaknesses but when you have bipolar 2 it s easy to focus on your weaknesses try to focus on your strengths instead what are you good at what do you enjoy doing give yourself credit for your accomplishments when you achieve something take a moment to celebrate your success don t let your inner critic tell you that your accomplishments don t matter practice self care self care is essential for everyone but it s especially important for people with bipolar 2 make sure you re getting enough sleep eating healthy foods and exercising regularly these things will help you feel better both physically and mentally get professional help if you re struggling to manage your bipolar 2 don t be afraid to get professional help a therapist can teach you coping skills and help you develop a treatment plan that works for you it takes time and effort to change your inner critic into an inner friend but it s worth it when you learn to be kinder to yourself you ll be happier and healthier here are some additional tips that may be helpful find a support group talking to other people who understand what you re going through can be very helpful there are many support groups available for people with bipolar 2 read self help books there are many self help books available that can provide helpful information and advice on living with bipolar 2 join an online forum there are many online forums where people with bipolar 2 can connect and support each other talk to your doctor your doctor can help you develop a treatment plan that s right for you they can also provide you with support and guidance remember you are not alone there are many people who understand what you re going through and want to help with the right support you can overcome bipolar 2 and live a happy and fulfilling life
